{"title_page": "Nicolas Szersze\u0144", "text_new": "{{short description|French-Polish volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name            = Nicolas Szersze\u0144\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| full_name       = \n| nickname        = \n| nationality     = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[France|French]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Poland|Polish]]  \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1996|12|31|df=y}}                \n| birth_place     = [[Poissy, France]]\n| hometown        = \n| height          = 1.95 m\n| weight          = 91 kg\n| spike           = 343 cm\n| college         = [[Ohio State University]]\n| position        = Outside hitter\n| currentclub     = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n| currentnumber   = 9\n| years           = 2015\u20132018<br>2018\u2013<br>2019\u20132020\n| teams           = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> \u2192 {{flagicon|POL}} [[\u015alepsk Suwa\u0142ki]]\n| nationalyears   = \n| nationalteam    = \n| medaltemplates  = \n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Szersze\u0144''' (born {{birth date|1996|12|31|df=yes}}) is a [[France|French]] [[volleyball]] player of [[Poland|Polish]] descent, a member of Polish club [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.assecoresovia.pl/2018/05/nicolas-szerszen-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii/ |title=Nicolas Szersze\u0144 przyjmuj\u0105cym Asseco Resovii! |work=www.assecoresovia.pl |language=pl |date=22 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/szerszen-signs-professional-contract-with-elite-polish-club/ |title=Szerszen Signs Professional Contract with Elite Polish Club |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=22 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nHis father \u2013 Jacek Szersze\u0144 was also a volleyball player playing in the top professional league in [[Poland]] as a member of [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w|Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]] and [[Hutnik Krak\u00f3w (volleyball)|Hutnik Krak\u00f3w]], two\u2013time [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] (1988, 1989) with the latter club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uks-hutnik.pl/historia-i-sukcesy/ |title=Historia i sukcesy |work=www.uks-hutnik.pl |language=pl |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n===College===\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament|NCAA National Championship]], with [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/national-champions-ohio-state-crowned-kings-of-mens-volleyball/ |title=NATIONAL CHAMPIONS! Ohio State Crowned Kings of Men's Volleyball |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n** '''2017''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2017 NCAA National Collegiate Men's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA National Championship]], with [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/no-1-ohio-state-wins-national-championship/ |title=No. 1 Ohio State wins National Championship |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=6 May 2017 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://siatka.org/pokaz/ohio-state-mistrzem-usa-szerszen-mvp/ |title=Ohio State mistrzem USA. Szersze\u0144 ponownie MVP |work=www.siatka.org |language=pl |date=7 May 2017 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team\n* '''2017:''' [[2017 NCAA National Collegiate Men's Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team (''Most Outstanding Player'')\n* '''2018:''' [[2018 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/historic-run-comes-to-an-end-in-2018-ncaa-semifinals/ |title=Historic Run Comes to an End in 2018 NCAA Semifinals |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/30505.html PlusLiga player profile]\n* [https://volleybox.net/nicolas-szerszen-p11496/clubs volleybox.net player profile]\n* [https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-volley/roster/season/2017-18/nicolas-szerszen/ Ohio State Buckeyes 2017-18 roster \u2013 Nicolas Szerszen]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szersze\u0144, Nicolas}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Poissy]]\n[[Category:French men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Polish men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French-Polish volleyball player}}\n{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name            = Nicolas Szersze\u0144\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| caption         = \n| full_name       = \n| nickname        = \n| nationality     = {{flagicon|FRA}} [[France|French]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Poland|Polish]]  \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1996|12|31|df=y}}                \n| birth_place     = [[Poissy, France]]\n| hometown        = \n| height          = 1.95 m\n| weight          = 91 kg\n| spike           = 343 cm\n| college         = [[Ohio State University]]\n| position        = Outside hitter\n| currentclub     = {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]\n| currentnumber   = 9\n| years           = 2015\u20132018<br>2018\u2013<br>2019\u20132020\n| teams           = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<br> {{flagicon|POL}} [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]]<br> \u2192 {{flagicon|POL}} [[\u015alepsk Suwa\u0142ki]]\n| nationalyears   = \n| nationalteam    = \n| medaltemplates  = \n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Szersze\u0144''' (born {{birth date|1996|12|31|df=yes}}) is a [[France|French]] [[volleyball]] player of [[Poland|Polish]] descent, a member of Polish club [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.assecoresovia.pl/2018/05/nicolas-szerszen-przyjmujacym-asseco-resovii/ |title=Nicolas Szersze\u0144 przyjmuj\u0105cym Asseco Resovii! |work=www.assecoresovia.pl |language=pl |date=22 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/szerszen-signs-professional-contract-with-elite-polish-club/ |title=Szerszen Signs Professional Contract with Elite Polish Club |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=22 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> His father \u2013 Jacek Szersze\u0144 was also a volleyball player playing in the top professional league in [[Poland]] as a member of [[Asseco Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w|Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w]] and [[Hutnik Krak\u00f3w (volleyball)|Hutnik Krak\u00f3w]], two\u2013time [[PlusLiga|Polish Champion]] (1988, 1989) with the latter club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uks-hutnik.pl/historia-i-sukcesy/ |title=Historia i sukcesy |work=www.uks-hutnik.pl |language=pl |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n===College===\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament|NCAA National Championship]], with [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/national-champions-ohio-state-crowned-kings-of-mens-volleyball/ |title=NATIONAL CHAMPIONS! Ohio State Crowned Kings of Men's Volleyball |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=7 May 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n** '''2017''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2017 NCAA National Collegiate Men's Volleyball Tournament|NCAA National Championship]], with [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball|Ohio State Buckeyes]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/no-1-ohio-state-wins-national-championship/ |title=No. 1 Ohio State wins National Championship |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=6 May 2017 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://siatka.org/pokaz/ohio-state-mistrzem-usa-szerszen-mvp/ |title=Ohio State mistrzem USA. Szersze\u0144 ponownie MVP |work=www.siatka.org |language=pl |date=7 May 2017 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team\n* '''2017:''' [[2017 NCAA National Collegiate Men's Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team (''Most Outstanding Player'')\n* '''2018:''' [[2018 NCAA Men's National Collegiate Volleyball Tournament#All-Tournament Team|NCAA National Championship]] \u2013 All-Tournament Team<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/historic-run-comes-to-an-end-in-2018-ncaa-semifinals/ |title=Historic Run Comes to an End in 2018 NCAA Semifinals |work=www.ohiostatebuckeyes.com |date=4 May 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.plusliga.pl/players/id/30505.html PlusLiga player profile]\n* [https://volleybox.net/nicolas-szerszen-p11496/clubs volleybox.net player profile]\n* [https://ohiostatebuckeyes.com/sports/m-volley/roster/season/2017-18/nicolas-szerszen/ Ohio State Buckeyes 2017-18 roster \u2013 Nicolas Szerszen]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szersze\u0144, Nicolas}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Poissy]]\n[[Category:French men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Polish men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Resovia Rzesz\u00f3w players]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolas_Szersze%C5%84"}
{"title_page": "Media of Transnistria", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|date=August 2009}}\n{{Culture of Transnistria}}\nThe '''media of [[Transnistria]]''', the breakaway territory within the borders of [[Moldova]], features both state-owned or supported outlets and opposition media. Publications are in [[Russian language|Russian]], with a single newspaper in each of the other two official languages, [[Moldovan language|Moldovan]] ([[Romanian language|Romanian]]), and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]. Allegations of [[propaganda]] have emerged internationally.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Media outlets==\n\n===Print media===\nTransnistria has 14 newspapers, including several daily papers. Some print media does not have a large circulation, and only appears on a weekly or monthly basis. The oldest newspaper is the \"[[Dnestrovskaya Pravda]]\", founded in 1941 in Tiraspol.\n\nThe [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] claims that the media climate in [[Transnistria]] is restrictive and that authorities of both banks of [[Dniester]] engage in efforts to silence their respective opposition.<ref>[http://www.osce.org/moldova/13427.html OSCE - Media in Transdniestria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909141956/http://www.osce.org/moldova/13427.html |date=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, according to the U.S. Department of State, authorities harassed independent newspapers when they criticized the Transnistrian government. Most Moldovan newspapers did not circulate widely in Transnistria, although they were available in Tiraspol.<ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2005/61664.htm U.S. Department of State report about Human Rights]</ref>\n\nHowever, several opposition newspapers exist in Transnistria. They include [[Rybnitsa]]-based \"Dobry Den\", \"Chelovek i ego prava\" (''Man and His Rights''), \"Novaya Gazeta\" from [[Tighina|Bender]], [[Russian Proriv! (Transnistrian newspaper)|\"Russian Proriv!\"]], \"Profsoyuznye Vesti\" and \"Glas Naroda.\"\n\nThe \"[[Tiraspol Times]]\" was an English-language website. Article from it were always featured in the official website Pridnestrovie.net.\n\nNewspapers published by the government or in favour of the government include \"[[Trudovoi Tiraspol]]\", \"Pridnestrovye\", \"Novy Dnestrovskiy Kuryer\", \"Gomin\" (in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]), \"Adev\u0103rul Nistrean\" (in [[Moldovan language|Moldovan]], but written in the [[Romanian Cyrillic alphabet|Cyrillic alphabet]]).\n\n===Radio broadcasting===\n<!--{{Main|Radio in Transnistria}}-->\nA stateowned radio station, \"Radio PMR\", broadcasts both via FM and on frequency 7290&nbsp;kHz shortwave, 41 meter band. Four privately owned commercial radio stations broadcast on FM from Transnistria. They are: \"Inter FM\", \"Dynamite FM\", \"EnergyRadio.FM\", \"Frequence3\". The owners of opposition newspaper \"Novaia Gazeta\" plan to establish an independent radio station.<ref>Mihai Grecu: ''\"The Policy of Linguistic Cleansing in Transnistria\"'', Institute of Political and Military Studies (Chisinau, Moldova - 2005)</ref>\n\n===Television broadcasting===\n<!--{{Main|Television in Transnistria}}-->\nThere are four TV channels in Transnistria. Two of them are local (to Tiraspol and Tighina/Bender), while two of them cover all of Transnistria.\n\nTelevision in Transnistria was for a long time dominated by the public service company [[TV PMR]]. In 1998, Transnistria's first commercial channel, \"TSV\" (''Television of Free Choice'') was started.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080221224443/http://pridnestrovie.net/tvradio.html \"TV and Radio: freedom of speech?\"]</ref> Cable network operator \"MultiTV\" carries 24 television channels for its \"premium\" package and 5 channels for \"social\" package.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv.sheriff.md/index_e.html |title=MultiChannel Television channel listings |access-date=2007-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702164653/http://www.tv.sheriff.md/index_e.html |archive-date=2007-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Moldovan TV stations from outside Transnistria are not available through cable but can be seen via an [[antenna (radio)|aerial]]. However [[ProTV]] and NIT, two private channel based in Chi\u015fin\u0103u, was introduced to on most cable networks in Transnistria from September 2009 and 1 November 2007 respectively.\n\n===Telecommunications===\n{{Main article|Telecommunications in Transnistria}}\n\n===Internet===\n<!--{{Main|Internet in Transnistria}}-->\n\nInternet media is both stateowned and privately operated. In Russian, the websites include [http://dniester.ru Dniester.Ru] (news agency),  [https://web.archive.org/web/20080524062603/http://olvia.idknet.com/ Olvia Press] (official state news agency), [https://web.archive.org/web/20031220180219/http://www.tiraspol.info/ Tiraspol Info] (news aggregator), [https://web.archive.org/web/20060627230717/http://pridnestrovie.info/ Pridnestrovie.info]. Many political organizations and government departments also have their own news services and online news pages, not listed here.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.catalog.tiraspol.net/ |title=PMR web directory |access-date=2020-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910061445/http://catalog.tiraspol.net/ |archive-date=2018-09-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''dniester.ru'' has been blocked by Transnistrian authorities since November 8, 2012 according to the website.\n\nIn August 2014, Yevgeny Shevchuk issued a decree on combating extremism that empowered the Transnistrian KGB to request the prosecutor's office to block internet content. Authorities would take such a determination following a review by a panel appointed by the KGB.<ref name=usstate />\n\n<!--===Internet censorship and surveillance===-->\n\n<!--\n==Media Organisations==\n===Media agencies===\n===Trade unions===\n===Regulatory authorities===\n\n==Censorship and media freedom==\n===Attacks and threats against journalists===\n===Political interferences===\n===Civil defamation lawsuits===\n===Cyber-attacks===\n===Smear campaigns===\n-->\n\n==Media freedom and pluralism==\nTransnistrian media environment is restrictive, and is dominated numerically by state-owned media (e.g. ''Pridnestrovie'' and ''Dnestrovskaya Pravda'', which are the region major newspapers<ref name=usstate />), or by media controlled through public institutions, such as State Tele-radio Company and State Service media. They are subsidized, heavily politicized, and do not criticize the authorities.<ref name=fw2016>{{cite web|title=Transnistria * - Country report - Freedom in the World - 2016|url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2016/transnistria|publisher=Freedom House|accessdate=10 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=ipre>{{cite web|last1=Chiveri|first1=Valeriu|title=Study: The media situation, perspectives, contacts and mutual perception between journalists from both banks of Nistru River|url=http://ipre.md/2016/06/23/studiu-situatia-in-domeniul-media-perspectivele-contactele-si-perceptia-jurnalistilor-de-pe-ambele-maluri-ale-nistrului/?lang=en|publisher=IPRE|accessdate=11 April 2017|date=2016-06-23}}</ref><ref name=irex>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= 2016|title= Media Sustainability Index Moldova |url= https://www.irex.org/sites/default/files/pdf/media-sustainability-index-europe-eurasia-2016-moldova.pdf.pdf|publisher= IREX|page= |docket= |access-date= 2017-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sheriff (company)|Sheriff]] company dominates the private media market, including private broadcasting, [[cable television]], and [[internet]] service.<ref name=fw2016 /> Sheriff represents a \"so-called opposition\" according to IPRE.<ref name=ipre /> According to an [[International Research & Exchanges Board|IREX]] report they serve the interest of the company.<ref name=irex />\n\nThere are some independent newspapers or magazines, with small circulation<ref name=fw2016 /> and little advertising,<ref name=irex /> but they have been able to create a space of freedom of expression.<ref name=ipre /> They receive threats from the authorities, that sometimes even take direct control.<ref name=usstate />\n\nThe government hinders critical media and journalists are intimidated.<ref name=ipre /> Since 2014 government agencies, private organizations, and citizens are required to report instances of \"extremist\" material online.<ref name=ipre /> Journalists expressing opinions different from those of the media owners are easily dismissed.<ref name=irex /> [[Self-censorship]] is practised, with local press avoiding subjects questioning the Transnistrian goal of independence or criticizing the pro-Russian foreign policy.<ref name=usstate />\n\n[[Media of Moldova]] have little presence in Transnistria,<ref name=ipre /> being available mainly in [[Tiraspol]].<ref name=usstate /> Moldovan channels are blocked. Moldovan journalists need accreditation to enter the country, and they are sometimes denied entrance or detained.<ref name=fw2016 />\n\nIn 2015 activist and journalist Serghei Ilcenko was detained for four months.<ref name=irex /><ref>{{cite news|title=Journalist jailed on extremism charges in Moldova's Transdniester region|url=https://cpj.org/2015/03/journalist-jailed-on-extremism-charges-in-moldovas.php|accessdate=29 April 2017|work=CPJ|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> The Transnistrian KGB then warned other activists who were accused of having posted \"extremist messages\" on the internet and, in general, warned internet users to trust only official sources, and not to contest Transnistrian independence.<ref name=usstate>{{cite web|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2015 - Moldova|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2015humanrightsreport/index.htm?dlid=252877&year=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503113158/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2015humanrightsreport/index.htm?dlid=252877&year=2015|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 May 2018|website=U.S. State Department|publisher=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2014 Transnistrian \u201cpolice\u201d detained a television crew from [[Publika Television]] while travelling to a school in [[Corjova, Dub\u0103sari|Corjova]] village to produce a piece on the first day of school at a Latin script school. Transnistrian police detained the crew on the grounds that they lacked a special authorization from the Transnistrian Security Service. After a few hours of interrogation, police released the crew.<ref name=usstate />\n\n==Transnistrian propaganda==\nIn 2006, ''[[The Economist]]'' reported that an alleged [[public diplomacy|propagandistic campaign]], aimed at English-speaking audience had been underway. This was done through an agency entitled the \"[[International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty]]\" (ICDISS).<ref name=\"Economist ICDISS\">[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 article in \"The Economist\"]</ref> It was claimed in The Economist that the ICDISS had links to a number of [[English language|English]]-language websites that were all pro-Transnistrian but had very few details about how and where they are produced. In particular, it highlighted the [[International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty|Wikipedia article]] on the group, [http://www.pridnestrovie.net/ Pridnestrovie.net] and [http://www.visitpmr.com/ Visitpmr.com]. The latter two are both described as \"propaganda sites for Transdniestria\".<ref>[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 The Economist] August 3rd 2006</ref> ''pridnestrovie.net'' and ''visitpmr.com'' have acknowledged help from the [[ICDISS]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=pridnestrovie&tld=net&x=25&y=9 |title=WHOIS on Pridnestrovie.net |access-date=2007-05-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927141548/https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=pridnestrovie&tld=net&x=25&y=9 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=visitpmr&tld=com&x=0&y=0 |title=WHOIS on Visitpmr.com |access-date=2007-05-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927141538/https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=visitpmr&tld=com&x=0&y=0 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ICDISS email is run by someone self-named Ms Stephenson, also interviewed in ''tiraspoltimes.com''.\n\n=== International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty===\nThe council is credited with producing a report in support of Transdniestrian independence. All but one of the alleged authors of the report has since denied involvement in the study. The case has provoked suspicions among Western officials like Louis O'Neill, the head of the OSCE Mission to Moldova.\nJournalist Edward Lucas, who wrote the original \"Economist\" story about the organization, says he could find little information about the think tank.\n\"What's really remarkable is that nobody's been able to produce any credible proof or verifiable proof that they have any existence,\" Lucas says.,<ref>[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 \"Economist\" - comments by Edward Lucas]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070402114539/http://www.icdiss.org/]</ref>\n\n===Pridnestrovie.net===\nThe websites quote a number of Westerners marvelling at Tiraspol's new football stadium or saying Transdniester is the French Riviera compared to Moldova proper.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pridnestrovie.net/ |title={{Dead link{{!}}date=July 2011}} |access-date=2012-09-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722091035/http://www.pridnestrovie.net/ |archive-date=2010-07-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nQuotes from the site:<br /> \n''It has a free market economy, 200% growth, and a multi-party democracy with the opposition in control of parliament.\n\n===Tiraspol Times (tiraspoltimes.com)===\nTiraspol Times was a short lived (2006\u20132008) English language news provider focused on [[Transnistria]]. It published an online newspaper, a free news feed service, and, according to its own site, a weekly colour magazine and a print newspaper in [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] format available at \"select locations\" in Transnistria, but not abroad and with no subscription available. It professed to be \"committed to the truth\" and whose content was largely dedicated to effusive praise of the government or endorsing independence.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090514035839/http://www.tiraspoltimes.com/ Archived link]</ref>\n\nOnline texts by the ''Tiraspol Times'' were licensed as freely distributable. Articles from it have been reprinted by [[UNPO]] and by the [[United Nations]]' ''Global Action on Aging,''<ref>[http://www.globalaging.org/pension/world/2006/moldova.htm \"Moldova: Parliament Takes on Smirnov Over Pension Reform\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727131759/http://www.globalaging.org/pension/world/2006/moldova.htm |date=2011-07-27 }}, October 10, 2006</ref> as well as various news organizations.\n\n''Tiraspol Times'' has been criticised as being strongly biased in favour of the Transnistrian authorities and Transnistrian independence.<ref name=\"rfe\">''[[Radio Free Europe]]'', [http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794de55d-f342-4f9d-8f1a-534a6ea58b78.html \"Moldova: In Cyberspace, Transdniester Doesn't Look That Bad\"], 15 September 2006</ref> A report in the ''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]]'' described it as part of a concerted online campaign to promote Transnistria through expertly produced websites, saying that its background and funding were largely undisclosed.<ref name=\"economist.com\">''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]], [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 \"Disinformation: Covering tracks - How to disguise, inflate and disappear on the internet\"]'', 3 August 2006</ref><ref>[http://edwardlucas.blogspot.com/2006/08/gotcha-2.html (same article, no subscription necessary)]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Radio Free Europe]]'' claims that its content was \"largely dedicated to effusive praise of the government or endorsing independence\".<ref name=\"rfe\"/> while the ''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]]'' associates them with [[ICDISS]], which it alleges is an [[astroturfing]] attempt. ''Economist'' also names ''Tiraspol Times'' an online magazine produced \"expertly, but mysteriously, in support of the authorities\".<ref name=\"economist.com\"/>\n\nThe site published few ads and its funding sources are not known. [[Edward Lucas (journalist)|Edward Lucas]], a journalist for ''Economist'', suggested it could have received its funding either from the government, from [[Vladimir Antyufeyev]]'s State Security Committee or from one of the Transnistrian companies.<ref name=\"rfe\"/>. This claim proved to be incorrect as it was in fact owned and funded by Desmond Grant, a prominent Irish newspaper publisher. \n\nTom de Waal, a London-based journalist and author, was outraged to see an article under his name appear on the \"Tiraspol Times\" website.\n\"I've certainly never been to Pridnestrovie, Transdneister, or Moldova, and I am certainly not arguing, as is written under my name, that Pridnestrovie has a better case for independence than Kosovo,\" de Waal says.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794DE55D-F342-4F9D-8F1A-534A6EA58B78.html Radio Free Europe - Comments by Tom de Waal]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Telecommunications in Transnistria]]\n* [[Human rights in Transnistria]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ijc.md/Publicatii/resurse/ghid_mass_media_2008.pdf Media Guide of the Republic of Moldova 2008] (also covers Transnistria. List of publishers, news agencies and broadcasters, in Romanian and English.)\n* [http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794DE55D-F342-4F9D-8F1A-534A6EA58B78.html Transdniester in Cyberspace] Radio Free Europe\n* [https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2014/transnistria Freedom House: Transnistria, 2014 Report]\n* [https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/186593.pdf \"Moldova\", state.gov (incl. Transnistria)], PDF\n* [http://www.kas.de/wf/en/71.13614/ Media Freedom in Moldova (incl. Transnistria)], KAS\n* [https://freedomhouse.org/sites/default/files/NIT2015_Moldova_0.pdf \"The Report on press freedom and media in Moldova\", 2015], Freedom House\n\n===Media websites===\n* [http://novostipmr.com/ru Novosti Pridnestrovia] {{in lang|ru}} \n<!-- * [http://www.president-pmr.org/radio/ Radio PMR] -->\n* [http://dniester.ru/taxonomy/term/47 DNIESTER.ru News & Articles] {{in lang|en|ru}}\n* [http://tiras.ru tiras.ru] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.vspmr.org/?Lang=Eng Parliamentary press service] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.pridnestrovie.de/radio-pmr-podcast.html Radio PMR - Podcast in English, German, French] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.tv-pmr.com/ TV PMR / TV PMR] {{in lang|ru}}\n<!-- * [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 Disinformation] The Economist - paysite -->\n<!-- * [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 Covering tracks] The Economist - paysite -->\n<!-- * [http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm 2004 Census results and comparation with 1989, by Olvia Press] - unrelated -->\n<!-- * [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005621/http://conflict.md/stiri.php?ID=1392 MOLDOVAN NGOs REGARD TRANSNISTRIAN REFERENDUM AS A FARCE] defunct and unrelated -->\n\n{{Europe topic|Media of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media Of Transnistria}}\n[[Category:Media of Transnistria|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup|date=August 2009}}\n{{Culture of Transnistria}}\nThe '''media of [[Transnistria]]''', the breakaway territory within the borders of [[Moldova]], features both state-owned or supported outlets and opposition media. Publications are in [[Russian language|Russian]], with a single newspaper in each of the other two official languages, [[Moldovan language|Moldovan]] ([[Romanian language|Romanian]]), and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]. Allegations of [[propaganda]] have emerged internationally.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Media outlets==\n\n===Print media===\nTransnistria has 14 newspapers, including several daily papers. Some print media does not have a large circulation, and only appears on a weekly or monthly basis. The oldest newspaper is the \"[[Dnestrovskaya Pravda]]\", founded in 1941 in Tiraspol.\n\nThe [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] claims that the media climate in [[Transnistria]] is restrictive and that authorities of both banks of [[Dniester]] engage in efforts to silence their respective opposition.<ref>[http://www.osce.org/moldova/13427.html OSCE - Media in Transdniestria] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909141956/http://www.osce.org/moldova/13427.html |date=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, according to the U.S. Department of State, authorities harassed independent newspapers when they criticized the Transnistrian government. Most Moldovan newspapers did not circulate widely in Transnistria, although they were available in Tiraspol.<ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2005/61664.htm U.S. Department of State report about Human Rights]</ref>\n\nHowever, several opposition newspapers exist in Transnistria. They include [[Rybnitsa]]-based \"Dobry Den\", \"Chelovek i ego prava\" (''Man and His Rights''), \"Novaya Gazeta\" from [[Tighina|Bender]], [[Russian Proriv! (Transnistrian newspaper)|\"Russian Proriv!\"]], \"Profsoyuznye Vesti\" and \"Glas Naroda.\"\n\nThe \"[[Tiraspol Times]]\" was an English-language website. Article from it were always featured in the official website Pridnestrovie.net.\n\nNewspapers published by the government or in favour of the government include \"[[Trudovoi Tiraspol]]\", \"Pridnestrovye\", \"Novy Dnestrovskiy Kuryer\", \"Gomin\" (in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]), \"Adev\u0103rul Nistrean\" (in [[Moldovan language|Moldovan]], but written in the [[Romanian Cyrillic alphabet|Cyrillic alphabet]]).\n\n===Radio broadcasting===\n<!--{{Main|Radio in Transnistria}}-->\nA stateowned radio station, \"Radio PMR\", broadcasts both via FM and on frequency 7290&nbsp;kHz shortwave, 41 meter band. Four privately owned commercial radio stations broadcast on FM from Transnistria. They are: \"Inter FM\", \"Dynamite FM\", \"EnergyRadio.FM\", \"Frequence3\". The owners of opposition newspaper \"Novaia Gazeta\" plan to establish an independent radio station.<ref>Mihai Grecu: ''\"The Policy of Linguistic Cleansing in Transnistria\"'', Institute of Political and Military Studies (Chisinau, Moldova - 2005)</ref>\n\n===Television broadcasting===\n<!--{{Main|Television in Transnistria}}-->\nThere are four TV channels in Transnistria. Two of them are local (to Tiraspol and Tighina/Bender), while two of them cover all of Transnistria.\n\nTelevision in Transnistria was for a long time dominated by the public service company [[TV PMR]]. In 1998, Transnistria's first commercial channel, \"TSV\" (''Television of Free Choice'') was started.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080221224443/http://pridnestrovie.net/tvradio.html \"TV and Radio: freedom of speech?\"]</ref> Cable network operator \"MultiTV\" carries 24 television channels for its \"premium\" package and 5 channels for \"social\" package.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tv.sheriff.md/index_e.html |title=MultiChannel Television channel listings |access-date=2007-02-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070702164653/http://www.tv.sheriff.md/index_e.html |archive-date=2007-07-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Moldovan TV stations from outside Transnistria are not available through cable but can be seen via an [[antenna (radio)|aerial]]. However [[ProTV]] and NIT, two private channel based in Chi\u015fin\u0103u, was introduced to on most cable networks in Transnistria from September 2009 and 1 November 2007 respectively.\n\n===Telecommunications===\n{{Main article|Telecommunications in Transnistria}}\n\n===Internet===\n<!--{{Main|Internet in Transnistria}}-->\n\nInternet media is both stateowned and privately operated. In Russian, the websites include [http://dniester.ru Dniester.Ru] (news agency),  [https://web.archive.org/web/20080524062603/http://olvia.idknet.com/ Olvia Press] (official state news agency), [https://web.archive.org/web/20031220180219/http://www.tiraspol.info/ Tiraspol Info] (news aggregator), [https://web.archive.org/web/20060627230717/http://pridnestrovie.info/ Pridnestrovie.info]. Many political organizations and government departments also have their own news services and online news pages, not listed here.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.catalog.tiraspol.net/ |title=PMR web directory |access-date=2020-01-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180910061445/http://catalog.tiraspol.net/ |archive-date=2018-09-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n''dniester.ru'' has been blocked by Transnistrian authorities since November 8, 2012 according to the website.\n\nIn August 2014, Yevgeny Shevchuk issued a decree on combating extremism that empowered the Transnistrian KGB to request the prosecutor's office to block internet content. Authorities would take such a determination following a review by a panel appointed by the KGB.<ref name=usstate />\n\n<!--===Internet censorship and surveillance===-->\n\n<!--\n==Media Organisations==\n===Media agencies===\n===Trade unions===\n===Regulatory authorities===\n\n==Censorship and media freedom==\n===Attacks and threats against journalists===\n===Political interferences===\n===Civil defamation lawsuits===\n===Cyber-attacks===\n===Smear campaigns===\n-->\n\n==Media freedom and pluralism==\nTransnistrian media environment is restrictive, and is dominated numerically by state-owned media (e.g. ''Pridnestrovie'' and ''Dnestrovskaya Pravda'', which are the region major newspapers<ref name=usstate />), or by media controlled through public institutions, such as State Tele-radio Company and State Service media. They are subsidized, heavily politicized, and do not criticize the authorities.<ref name=fw2016>{{cite web|title=Transnistria * - Country report - Freedom in the World - 2016|url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2016/transnistria|publisher=Freedom House|accessdate=10 April 2017}}</ref><ref name=ipre>{{cite web|last1=Chiveri|first1=Valeriu|title=Study: The media situation, perspectives, contacts and mutual perception between journalists from both banks of Nistru River|url=http://ipre.md/2016/06/23/studiu-situatia-in-domeniul-media-perspectivele-contactele-si-perceptia-jurnalistilor-de-pe-ambele-maluri-ale-nistrului/?lang=en|publisher=IPRE|accessdate=11 April 2017|date=2016-06-23}}</ref><ref name=irex>{{cite report |author= |author-link= |authors= |date= 2016|title= Media Sustainability Index Moldova |url= https://www.irex.org/sites/default/files/pdf/media-sustainability-index-europe-eurasia-2016-moldova.pdf.pdf|publisher= IREX|page= |docket= |access-date= 2017-04-12 }}</ref>\n\n[[Sheriff (company)|Sheriff]] company dominates the private media market, including private broadcasting, [[cable television]], and [[internet]] service.<ref name=fw2016 /> Sheriff represents a \"so-called opposition\" according to IPRE.<ref name=ipre /> According to an [[International Research & Exchanges Board|IREX]] report they serve the interest of the company.<ref name=irex />\n\nThere are some independent newspapers or magazines, with small circulation<ref name=fw2016 /> and little advertising,<ref name=irex /> but they have been able to create a space of freedom of expression.<ref name=ipre /> They receive threats from the authorities, that sometimes even take direct control.<ref name=usstate />\n\nThe government hinders critical media and journalists are intimidated.<ref name=ipre /> Since 2014 government agencies, private organizations, and citizens are required to report instances of \"extremist\" material online.<ref name=ipre /> Journalists expressing opinions different from those of the media owners are easily dismissed.<ref name=irex /> [[Self-censorship]] is practised, with local press avoiding subjects questioning the Transnistrian goal of independence or criticizing the pro-Russian foreign policy.<ref name=usstate />\n\n[[Media of Moldova]] have little presence in Transnistria,<ref name=ipre /> being available mainly in [[Tiraspol]].<ref name=usstate /> Moldovan channels are blocked. Moldovan journalists need accreditation to enter the country, and they are sometimes denied entrance or detained.<ref name=fw2016 />\n\nIn 2015 activist and journalist Serghei Ilcenko was detained for four months.<ref name=irex /><ref>{{cite news|title=Journalist jailed on extremism charges in Moldova's Transdniester region|url=https://cpj.org/2015/03/journalist-jailed-on-extremism-charges-in-moldovas.php|accessdate=29 April 2017|work=CPJ|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> The Transnistrian KGB then warned other activists who were accused of having posted \"extremist messages\" on the internet and, in general, warned internet users to trust only official sources, and not to contest Transnistrian independence.<ref name=usstate>{{cite web|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2015 - Moldova|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2015humanrightsreport/index.htm?dlid=252877&year=2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503113158/https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2015humanrightsreport/index.htm?dlid=252877&year=2015|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 May 2018|website=U.S. State Department|publisher=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor|accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2014 Transnistrian \u201cpolice\u201d detained a television crew from [[Publika Television]] while travelling to a school in [[Corjova, Dub\u0103sari|Corjova]] village to produce a piece on the first day of school at a Latin script school. Transnistrian police detained the crew on the grounds that they lacked a special authorization from the Transnistrian Security Service. After a few hours of interrogation, police released the crew.<ref name=usstate />\n\n==Transnistrian propaganda==\nIn 2006, ''[[The Economist]]'' reported that an alleged [[public diplomacy|propagandistic campaign]], aimed at English-speaking audience had been underway. This was done through an agency entitled the \"[[International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty]]\" (ICDISS).<ref name=\"Economist ICDISS\">[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 article in \"The Economist\"]</ref> It was claimed in The Economist that the ICDISS had links to a number of [[English language|English]]-language websites that were all pro-Transnistrian but had very few details about how and where they are produced. In particular, it highlighted the [[International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty|Wikipedia article]] on the group, [http://www.pridnestrovie.net/ Pridnestrovie.net] and [http://www.visitpmr.com/ Visitpmr.com]. The latter two are both described as \"propaganda sites for Transdniestria\".<ref>[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 The Economist] August 3rd 2006</ref> ''pridnestrovie.net'' and ''visitpmr.com'' have acknowledged help from the [[ICDISS]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=pridnestrovie&tld=net&x=25&y=9 |title=WHOIS on Pridnestrovie.net |access-date=2007-05-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927141548/https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=pridnestrovie&tld=net&x=25&y=9 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=visitpmr&tld=com&x=0&y=0 |title=WHOIS on Visitpmr.com |access-date=2007-05-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927141538/https://www.srsplus.com/en-def-0a7367af863a/cgi-bin/whois.cgi?domain=visitpmr&tld=com&x=0&y=0 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The ICDISS email is run by someone self-named Ms Stephenson, also interviewed in ''tiraspoltimes.com''.\n\n=== International Council for Democratic Institutions and State Sovereignty===\nThe council is credited with producing a report in support of Transdniestrian independence. All but one of the alleged authors of the report has since denied involvement in the study. The case has provoked suspicions among Western officials like Louis O'Neill, the head of the OSCE Mission to Moldova.\nJournalist Edward Lucas, who wrote the original \"Economist\" story about the organization, says he could find little information about the think tank.\n\"What's really remarkable is that nobody's been able to produce any credible proof or verifiable proof that they have any existence,\" Lucas says.,<ref>[http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 \"Economist\" - comments by Edward Lucas]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070402114539/http://www.icdiss.org/]</ref>\n\n===Pridnestrovie.net===\nThe websites quote a number of Westerners marvelling at Tiraspol's new football stadium or saying Transdniester is the French Riviera compared to Moldova proper.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pridnestrovie.net/ |title={{Dead link{{!}}date=July 2011}} |access-date=2012-09-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722091035/http://www.pridnestrovie.net/ |archive-date=2010-07-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nQuotes from the site:<br /> \n''It has a free market economy, 200% growth, and a multi-party democracy with the opposition in control of parliament.\n\n===Tiraspol Times (tiraspoltimes.com)===\nTiraspol Times was a short lived (2006\u20132008) English language news provider focused on [[Transnistria]]. It published an online newspaper, a free news feed service, and, according to its own site, a weekly colour magazine and a print newspaper in [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] format available at \"select locations\" in Transnistria, but not abroad and with no subscription available. It professed to be \"committed to the truth\" and whose content was largely dedicated to effusive praise of the government or endorsing independence.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090514035839/http://www.tiraspoltimes.com/ Archived link]</ref>\n\nOnline texts by the ''Tiraspol Times'' were licensed as freely distributable. Articles from it have been reprinted by [[UNPO]] and by the [[United Nations]]' ''Global Action on Aging,''<ref>[http://www.globalaging.org/pension/world/2006/moldova.htm \"Moldova: Parliament Takes on Smirnov Over Pension Reform\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727131759/http://www.globalaging.org/pension/world/2006/moldova.htm |date=2011-07-27 }}, October 10, 2006</ref> as well as various news organizations.\n\n''Tiraspol Times'' has been criticised as being strongly biased in favour of the Transnistrian authorities and Transnistrian independence.<ref name=\"rfe\">''[[Radio Free Europe]]'', [http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794de55d-f342-4f9d-8f1a-534a6ea58b78.html \"Moldova: In Cyberspace, Transdniester Doesn't Look That Bad\"], 15 September 2006</ref> A report in the ''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]]'' described it as part of a concerted online campaign to promote Transnistria through expertly produced websites, saying that its background and funding were largely undisclosed.<ref name=\"economist.com\">''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]], [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 \"Disinformation: Covering tracks - How to disguise, inflate and disappear on the internet\"]'', 3 August 2006</ref><ref>[http://edwardlucas.blogspot.com/2006/08/gotcha-2.html (same article, no subscription necessary)]</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Radio Free Europe]]'' claims that its content was \"largely dedicated to effusive praise of the government or endorsing independence\".,<ref name=\"rfe\"/> while the ''[[Economist (magazine)|Economist]]'' associates them with [[ICDISS]], which it alleges is an [[astroturfing]] attempt. ''Economist'' also names ''Tiraspol Times'' an online magazine produced \"expertly, but mysteriously, in support of the authorities\".<ref name=\"economist.com\"/>\n\nThe site published few ads and its funding sources are not known. [[Edward Lucas (journalist)|Edward Lucas]], a journalist for ''Economist'', suggested it could have received its funding either from the government, from [[Vladimir Antyufeyev]]'s State Security Committee or from one of the Transnistrian companies.<ref name=\"rfe\"/>. This claim proved to be incorrect as it was in fact owned and funded by Desmond Grant, a prominent Irish newspaper publisher. \n\nTom de Waal, a London-based journalist and author, was outraged to see an article under his name appear on the \"Tiraspol Times\" website.\n\"I've certainly never been to Pridnestrovie, Transdneister, or Moldova, and I am certainly not arguing, as is written under my name, that Pridnestrovie has a better case for independence than Kosovo,\" de Waal says.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794DE55D-F342-4F9D-8F1A-534A6EA58B78.html Radio Free Europe - Comments by Tom de Waal]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Telecommunications in Transnistria]]\n* [[Human rights in Transnistria]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ijc.md/Publicatii/resurse/ghid_mass_media_2008.pdf Media Guide of the Republic of Moldova 2008] (also covers Transnistria. List of publishers, news agencies and broadcasters, in Romanian and English.)\n* [http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/09/794DE55D-F342-4F9D-8F1A-534A6EA58B78.html Transdniester in Cyberspace] Radio Free Europe\n* [https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2014/transnistria Freedom House: Transnistria, 2014 Report]\n* [https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/186593.pdf \"Moldova\", state.gov (incl. Transnistria)], PDF\n* [http://www.kas.de/wf/en/71.13614/ Media Freedom in Moldova (incl. Transnistria)], KAS\n* [https://freedomhouse.org/sites/default/files/NIT2015_Moldova_0.pdf \"The Report on press freedom and media in Moldova\", 2015], Freedom House\n\n===Media websites===\n* [http://novostipmr.com/ru Novosti Pridnestrovia] {{in lang|ru}} \n<!-- * [http://www.president-pmr.org/radio/ Radio PMR] -->\n* [http://dniester.ru/taxonomy/term/47 DNIESTER.ru News & Articles] {{in lang|en|ru}}\n* [http://tiras.ru tiras.ru] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.vspmr.org/?Lang=Eng Parliamentary press service] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.pridnestrovie.de/radio-pmr-podcast.html Radio PMR - Podcast in English, German, French] {{in lang|de}}\n* [http://www.tv-pmr.com/ TV PMR / TV PMR] {{in lang|ru}}\n<!-- * [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7252974 Disinformation] The Economist - paysite -->\n<!-- * [http://www.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=7258534 Covering tracks] The Economist - paysite -->\n<!-- * [http://www.olvia.idknet.com/ol37-09-05.htm 2004 Census results and comparation with 1989, by Olvia Press] - unrelated -->\n<!-- * [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005621/http://conflict.md/stiri.php?ID=1392 MOLDOVAN NGOs REGARD TRANSNISTRIAN REFERENDUM AS A FARCE] defunct and unrelated -->\n\n{{Europe topic|Media of}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media Of Transnistria}}\n[[Category:Media of Transnistria|*]]\n", "name_user": "Derim Hunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTiraspol Times (tiraspoltimes.com)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_of_Transnistria"}
{"title_page": "Hebrew Wikipedia", "text_new": "{{short description|Hebrew edition of Wikipedia}}\n{{Distinguish|Yiddish Wikipedia}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = {{Wiki favicon}} Hebrew Wikipedia\n| screenshot = Hebrew wikipedia main page 2010.png\n| screenshot_size = 240px\n| logo = Wikipedia-logo-v2-he.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| caption = Snapshot of Hebrew Wikipedia main page, 2010\n| url = [http://he.wikipedia.org/ he.wikipedia.org]\n| commercial = No\n| location = \n| type = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language = [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n| registration = Optional\n| owner = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| author =\n}}\n'''Hebrew Wikipedia''' ({{lang-he|\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea}}, {{IPA-he|viki\u02c8pedja ha(\u0294)entsiklo\u02c8pedja ha\u03c7of\u02c8\u0283it|IPA}}) is the [[Modern Hebrew|Hebrew language]] edition of [[Wikipedia]]. This edition was started on 11 May 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikipedia-l/2001-May/000116.html|title=Wikipedia-l new language wikis}}</ref> and contains more than {{formatnum:{{#expr:{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|he}} round -3}}}} [[encyclopedia article|articles]] as of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}.\n\n==History==\n[[File:150000HebWiki.png|thumb|Hebrew Wikipedia logo marking 150,000 articles]]\n===Timeline ===\n*'''July 8, 2003''': The Hebrew edition of Wikipedia was launched.\n* '''October 25, 2003''': The 1,000th article was written.\n* '''July 22, 2004''': The first meeting of Hebrew Wikipedians took place in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]].\n* '''September 10, 2004''': The 10,000th article was written.\n* '''September 20, 2004''': The [[:he:\u05d3\u05d2\u05dc \u05e7\u05d6\u05d7\u05e1\u05d8\u05df|Hebrew version]] of the [[Flag of Kazakhstan]] article became the one millionth article created in all Wikipedias.\n* '''December 24, 2006''': The 50,000th article was written.\n* '''January 10, 2010''': The 100,000th article was written.\n* '''August 29, 2013''': The 150,000th article was written.\n* '''December 28, 2016''': The 200,000th article was written.\n[[File:5YearsHeWP02.png|thumb|Hebrew Wikipedia's 5th birthday logo]] \nHebrew Wikipedia features several organized article writing projects, among them Wikitort - an academic project to write original articles about [[tort law]],<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d8 WIKITORT]]</ref> PhysiWiki - a project to write and improve articles about [[Physics]] with the cooperation of [[Weizmann Institute of Science]],<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d9\u05d6\u05de\u05d9 \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4/\u05e4\u05d9\u05d6\u05d9\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9]]</ref> and ongoing academic projects.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea]]</ref> Another major topic is [[Jewish history]] and the [[History of Israel]]. In 2006, the Elef Millim project<ref>[[:meta:Elef Millim project]]</ref> ({{lang-en|Thousand Words/Thousand Miles project}}) was launched to provide Wikipedia with free images. Groups of Wikipedians meet for field trips around the country to take pictures of Israeli sites. \n \n[[Hebrew spelling]] is a matter of debate. Since the standards published by the [[Academy of the Hebrew Language]] are not always meticulously followed in common usage,  the Hebrew Wikipedia community decides on problematic cases of spelling through discussion and polls to ensure  consistency. When technically possible, spelling decisions are periodically enforced using automatic replacement by a [[Internet bot|bot]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Shai | first=David | title=Wikipedia's good bots fixing Hebrew language entries | website=ynetnews | date=21 April 2019 | url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5495954,00.html | access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHebrew Wikipedia's requirements for [[Wikipedia:Notability|notability]] standards are relatively strict.\n\nHebrew Wikipedia organizes yearly competitions, sometimes with the assistance of the [[Wikimedia foundation]], as well as social gatherings and picnics.\n\n==2010 Knesset meeting==\n[[File:Roaring Lion 2014 award to Wikimedia Israel.jpg|thumb|The ''Roaring Lion 2014'' awarded by the Israel Public Relations Associations]]\nOn the occasion of the 100,000 articles milestone, the Science and Technology Committee of the [[Knesset]] (Israeli parliament) invited Wikipedia contributors and users to the 2 February 2010 morning meeting, to join in a debate about Wikipedia and other [[open-source software|open-source]] resources. Some Wikipedia contributors at the meeting criticized \"the lack of government cooperation with their efforts to compile a free online Hebrew-language encyclopedia,\" as well as sharing complaints from Wikipedia editors abroad that since the [[Israel Defense Forces]] does not release photos for [[copyleft|free redistribution]] on the Internet, the sole source of available pictures for entries such as the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] and the [[2006 Lebanon War]] are the [[Palestinian people|Palestinians]].<ref>{{cite news\n| first = | last =| authorlink =| author =Rebecca Anna Stoil| title =Is Wikipedia good for the Jews?| url = http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Article.aspx?id=167613| format =| work =| publisher = [[Jerusalem Post]]| location =| id =| pages =| page =| date = 2 February 2010| accessdate =| archiveurl =| archivedate =}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison with other language editions==\nIn July 2006, Hebrew Wikipedia had one of the highest number of bytes per article, and the highest of all editions on Wikipedia with over 20,000 articles.<ref>[http://stats.wikimedia.org/EN/TablesArticlesBytesPerArticle.htm Wikimedia Statistics Tool]</ref>\n\nWhereas the English Wikipedia requires a general consensus for deleting articles (hence deletion discussion is not considered to be a voting process), the Hebrew Wikipedia has adopted a policy of deletion upon a 55% majority, with no minimum number of votes.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05de\u05d7\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4|Hebrew Wikipedia deletion policy page]]</ref> In these votes, only registered users with one month seniority and at least 100 edits in the article, image, category or template namespaces in the past 90 days can vote.\n\n==Strict inclusion criteria==\nCompared to English Wikipedia, Hebrew Wikipedia is more conservative with respect to content.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d4 \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e0\u05e0\u05d4]]</ref> \n\nThe inclusion criteria are detailed under the \"principles and guidelines\" page.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref> Some examples:\n* Articles on porn movies will be deleted unless they became cultural symbols.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05e0\u05d5\u05d2\u05e8\u05e4\u05d9\u05d4]]</ref> \n* Articles on porn stars will be deleted unless they have other notable aspects in their lives. \n* A book has to meet one of these four criteria: published by a known publisher, sold 10,000 copies, won a prize, or received good reviews.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Writers have to write at least two books to be notable as writers.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Singers and bands must have an album to their credit.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Articles on student films are deleted unless they win first prize in a film festival or were screened in mainstream cinemas.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d8\u05d5\u05d3\u05e0\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n\nList articles are rare.  In particular, lists of TV series episodes are not accepted, even as part of the articles on the series.\n\nOther controversial topics are articles of about small schools and minor educational institutions.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea/\u05de\u05d5\u05e1\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea]]</ref>\n\n==\"Hamichlol\" mirror for ultra-Orthodox==\n{{main|Hamichlol}}\n\nMany Ultra-Orthodox Jews refrain from using the Internet in an open way.\n\nHamichlol is a mirror site which includes a selection of wikipedia entries.{{CN|date=October 2019}}\n\nMajor differences are:\nnot all articles are copied.\nSome entries are re-edited to be more acceptable to Ultra-Orthodox readers.\n\n==Topics==\nIn 2019 the Hebrew Wikipedia has 71 thousand unique categories. The average article in this language version has 10 categories, while number of unique categories per articles ratio is 0.295. The largest number of articles has People (19%) and Geography (13%) category. In Hebrew Wikipedia articles related to Events and Society has the highest average quality. Content about Events is read more often and articles in Entertainment category have the highest authors' interest on average.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lewoniewski |first1=W\u0142odzimierz |last2=W\u0119cel |first2=Krzysztof |last3=Abramowicz |first3=Witold |date=2019 |title=Multilingual Ranking of Wikipedia Articles with Quality and Popularity Assessment in Different Topics |journal=Computers |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=60 |doi=10.3390/computers8030060 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wikimedia Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{InterWiki|code=he}}\n* {{in lang|he}} [http://he.wikipedia.org Hebrew Wikipedia]\n*{{cite web | last=Spiro | first=Amy | title=What did Israelis look up on Wikipedia in 2018? | website=The Jerusalem Post | date=7 January 2019 | url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/What-did-Israelis-look-up-on-Wikipedia-in-2018-576589 | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=After uploading 28,000 historical images, Wikimedia signs deal with National Library of Israel | website=haaretz.com | date=26 February 2019 | url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-after-uploading-28-000-historical-images-wikimedia-signs-deal-with-national-library-1.6976376 | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=Israel-edit-a-thon at Wikipedia Germany| website=i24NEWS | url=https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/128026-161018-israel-edit-a-thon-at-wikipedia-germany | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | last=Kalman | first=Aaron | title=Wikipedians most likely to war over 'Israel,' 'God' | website=The Times of Israel | date=3 June 2013 | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/wikipedians-most-likely-to-war-over-israel-god/ | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n\n{{Wikipedias}}\n\n[[Category:Hebrew-language encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Wikipedias by language]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hebrew edition of Wikipedia}}\n{{Distinguish|Yiddish Wikipedia}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = {{Wiki favicon}} Hebrew Wikipedia\n| screenshot = Hebrew wikipedia main page 2010.png\n| screenshot_size = 240px\n| logo = Wikipedia-logo-v2-he.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| caption = Snapshot of Hebrew Wikipedia main page, 2010\n| url = [http://he.wikipedia.org/ he.wikipedia.org]\n| commercial = No\n| location = \n| type = [[Internet encyclopedia project]]\n| language = [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]\n| registration = Optional\n| owner = [[Wikimedia Foundation]]\n| author =\n}}\n'''Hebrew Wikipedia''' ({{lang-he|\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea}}, {{IPA-he|viki\u02c8pedja ha(\u0294)entsiklo\u02c8pedja ha\u03c7of\u02c8\u0283it|IPA}}) is the [[Modern Hebrew|Hebrew language]] edition of [[Wikipedia]]. This edition was started on 11 May 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikipedia-l/2001-May/000116.html|title=Wikipedia-l new language wikis}}</ref> and contains more than {{formatnum:{{#expr:{{NUMBEROF|ARTICLES|he}} round -3}}}} [[encyclopedia article|articles]] as of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}.\n\n==History==\n[[File:150000HebWiki.png|thumb|Hebrew Wikipedia logo marking 150,000 articles]]\n===Timeline ===\n*'''69' 420''': The Hebrew edition of Wikipedia was launched.\n* '''October 25, 2003''': The 1,000th article was written.\n* '''July 22, 2004''': The first meeting of Hebrew Wikipedians took place in [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]].\n* '''September 10, 2004''': The 10,000th article was written.\n* '''September 20, 2004''': The [[:he:\u05d3\u05d2\u05dc \u05e7\u05d6\u05d7\u05e1\u05d8\u05df|Hebrew version]] of the [[Flag of Kazakhstan]] article became the one millionth article created in all Wikipedias.\n* '''December 24, 2006''': The 50,000th article was written.\n* '''January 10, 2010''': The 100,000th article was written.\n* '''August 29, 2013''': The 150,000th article was written.\n* '''December 28, 2016''': The 200,000th article was written.\n[[File:5YearsHeWP02.png|thumb|Hebrew Wikipedia's 5th birthday logo]] \nHebrew Wikipedia features several organized article writing projects, among them Wikitort - an academic project to write original articles about [[tort law]],<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d8 WIKITORT]]</ref> PhysiWiki - a project to write and improve articles about [[Physics]] with the cooperation of [[Weizmann Institute of Science]],<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d9\u05d6\u05de\u05d9 \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4/\u05e4\u05d9\u05d6\u05d9\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9]]</ref> and ongoing academic projects.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea]]</ref> Another major topic is [[Jewish history]] and the [[History of Israel]]. In 2006, the Elef Millim project<ref>[[:meta:Elef Millim project]]</ref> ({{lang-en|Thousand Words/Thousand Miles project}}) was launched to provide Wikipedia with free images. Groups of Wikipedians meet for field trips around the country to take pictures of Israeli sites. \n \n[[Hebrew spelling]] is a matter of debate. Since the standards published by the [[Academy of the Hebrew Language]] are not always meticulously followed in common usage,  the Hebrew Wikipedia community decides on problematic cases of spelling through discussion and polls to ensure  consistency. When technically possible, spelling decisions are periodically enforced using automatic replacement by a [[Internet bot|bot]].<ref>{{cite web | last=Shai | first=David | title=Wikipedia's good bots fixing Hebrew language entries | website=ynetnews | date=21 April 2019 | url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5495954,00.html | access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHebrew Wikipedia's requirements for [[Wikipedia:Notability|notability]] standards are relatively strict.\n\nHebrew Wikipedia organizes yearly competitions, sometimes with the assistance of the [[Wikimedia foundation]], as well as social gatherings and picnics.\n\n==2010 Knesset meeting==\n[[File:Roaring Lion 2014 award to Wikimedia Israel.jpg|thumb|The ''Roaring Lion 2014'' awarded by the Israel Public Relations Associations]]\nOn the occasion of the 100,000 articles milestone, the Science and Technology Committee of the [[Knesset]] (Israeli parliament) invited Wikipedia contributors and users to the 2 February 2010 morning meeting, to join in a debate about Wikipedia and other [[open-source software|open-source]] resources. Some Wikipedia contributors at the meeting criticized \"the lack of government cooperation with their efforts to compile a free online Hebrew-language encyclopedia,\" as well as sharing complaints from Wikipedia editors abroad that since the [[Israel Defense Forces]] does not release photos for [[copyleft|free redistribution]] on the Internet, the sole source of available pictures for entries such as the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] and the [[2006 Lebanon War]] are the [[Palestinian people|Palestinians]].<ref>{{cite news\n| first = | last =| authorlink =| author =Rebecca Anna Stoil| title =Is Wikipedia good for the Jews?| url = http://www.jpost.com/Israel/Article.aspx?id=167613| format =| work =| publisher = [[Jerusalem Post]]| location =| id =| pages =| page =| date = 2 February 2010| accessdate =| archiveurl =| archivedate =}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison with other language editions==\nIn July 2006, Hebrew Wikipedia had one of the highest number of bytes per article, and the highest of all editions on Wikipedia with over 20,000 articles.<ref>[http://stats.wikimedia.org/EN/TablesArticlesBytesPerArticle.htm Wikimedia Statistics Tool]</ref>\n\nWhereas the English Wikipedia requires a general consensus for deleting articles (hence deletion discussion is not considered to be a voting process), the Hebrew Wikipedia has adopted a policy of deletion upon a 55% majority, with no minimum number of votes.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d3\u05d9\u05e0\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05de\u05d7\u05d9\u05e7\u05d4|Hebrew Wikipedia deletion policy page]]</ref> In these votes, only registered users with one month seniority and at least 100 edits in the article, image, category or template namespaces in the past 90 days can vote.\n\n==Strict inclusion criteria==\nCompared to English Wikipedia, Hebrew Wikipedia is more conservative with respect to content.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05de\u05d4 \u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e0\u05e0\u05d4]]</ref> \n\nThe inclusion criteria are detailed under the \"principles and guidelines\" page.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref> Some examples:\n* Articles on porn movies will be deleted unless they became cultural symbols.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05e0\u05d5\u05d2\u05e8\u05e4\u05d9\u05d4]]</ref> \n* Articles on porn stars will be deleted unless they have other notable aspects in their lives. \n* A book has to meet one of these four criteria: published by a known publisher, sold 10,000 copies, won a prize, or received good reviews.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e1\u05e4\u05e8\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Writers have to write at least two books to be notable as writers.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Singers and bands must have an album to their credit.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n* Articles on student films are deleted unless they win first prize in a film festival or were screened in mainstream cinemas.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05e2\u05e7\u05e8\u05d5\u05e0\u05d5\u05ea \u05d5\u05e7\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd \u05de\u05e0\u05d7\u05d9\u05dd \u05dc\u05d9\u05e6\u05d9\u05e8\u05ea \u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d9\u05dd/\u05e1\u05e8\u05d8\u05d9 \u05e1\u05d8\u05d5\u05d3\u05e0\u05d8\u05d9\u05dd]]</ref>\n\nList articles are rare.  In particular, lists of TV series episodes are not accepted, even as part of the articles on the series.\n\nOther controversial topics are articles of about small schools and minor educational institutions.<ref>[[:he:\u05d5\u05d9\u05e7\u05d9\u05e4\u05d3\u05d9\u05d4:\u05d2\u05d1\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05ea/\u05de\u05d5\u05e1\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea]]</ref>\n\n==\"Hamichlol\" mirror for ultra-Orthodox==\n{{main|Hamichlol}}\n\nMany Ultra-Orthodox Jews refrain from using the Internet in an open way.\n\nHamichlol is a mirror site which includes a selection of wikipedia entries.{{CN|date=October 2019}}\n\nMajor differences are:\nnot all articles are copied.\nSome entries are re-edited to be more acceptable to Ultra-Orthodox readers.\n\n==Topics==\nIn 2019 the Hebrew Wikipedia has 71 thousand unique categories. The average article in this language version has 10 categories, while number of unique categories per articles ratio is 0.295. The largest number of articles has People (19%) and Geography (13%) category. In Hebrew Wikipedia articles related to Events and Society has the highest average quality. Content about Events is read more often and articles in Entertainment category have the highest authors' interest on average.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lewoniewski |first1=W\u0142odzimierz |last2=W\u0119cel |first2=Krzysztof |last3=Abramowicz |first3=Witold |date=2019 |title=Multilingual Ranking of Wikipedia Articles with Quality and Popularity Assessment in Different Topics |journal=Computers |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=60 |doi=10.3390/computers8030060 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Wikimedia Israel]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{InterWiki|code=he}}\n* {{in lang|he}} [http://he.wikipedia.org Hebrew Wikipedia]\n*{{cite web | last=Spiro | first=Amy | title=What did Israelis look up on Wikipedia in 2018? | website=The Jerusalem Post | date=7 January 2019 | url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/What-did-Israelis-look-up-on-Wikipedia-in-2018-576589 | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=After uploading 28,000 historical images, Wikimedia signs deal with National Library of Israel | website=haaretz.com | date=26 February 2019 | url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-after-uploading-28-000-historical-images-wikimedia-signs-deal-with-national-library-1.6976376 | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | title=Israel-edit-a-thon at Wikipedia Germany| website=i24NEWS | url=https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/europe/128026-161018-israel-edit-a-thon-at-wikipedia-germany | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n*{{cite web | last=Kalman | first=Aaron | title=Wikipedians most likely to war over 'Israel,' 'God' | website=The Times of Israel | date=3 June 2013 | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/wikipedians-most-likely-to-war-over-israel-god/ | access-date=24 October 2019}}\n\n{{Wikipedias}}\n\n[[Category:Hebrew-language encyclopedias]]\n[[Category:Wikipedias by language]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Hebrew-language websites]]\n", "name_user": "\u05e9\u05d5\u05e7\u05d5 \u05de\u05d5\u05e7\u05d4", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing Memes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hebrew_Wikipedia"}
{"title_page": "Bulbon Osman", "text_new": "{{infobox person\n| name = Bulbon Osman\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1940|03|18}}\n| birth_place = Jhamatia, [[Howrah district|Howrah]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]]\n| awards = [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1973)\n| relatives = [[Shawkat Osman]] (father)<br>[[Yeafesh Osman]] (brother)\n| alma_mater = [[University of Dhaka]]\n}}\n'''Bulbon Osman''' (born 18 March 1940) is a [[Bangladesh]]i academic, writer and artist. He was conferred [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] in 1973 for his contribution in juvenile literature.\n\n==Early life and education==\nOsman was born on 18 March 1940 at his maternal house at Jhamatia in [[Howrah district|Howrah]].<ref name=a/> He is the eldest son of [[Shawkat Osman]] and Saleha Osman. His brother [[Yeafesh Osman]] is the incumbent minister of [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://web.dailyjanakantha.com/details/article/421901/\u0995\u09a5\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c0-\u09b6\u0993\u0995\u09a4-\u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0-\u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u0995\u09c0-\u0986\u099c/|title=\u0995\u09a5\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c0 \u09b6\u0993\u0995\u09a4 \u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u0995\u09c0 \u0986\u099c|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=14 February 2020|newspaper=Janakantha|language=bn}}</ref>\n\nOsman's paternal house is situated at Sabalsinghapur in [[Hooghly district|Hooghly]].<ref name=a/> His family moved to [[Chittagong]] in 1950. After completing school and college life from there he got admitted into [[University of Dhaka]]. He was a student of the sociology department of the institution.<ref name=a/>\n\n==Career==\nOsman was appointed as a lecturer of the art related sociology at [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka|East Pakistan College of Arts and Crafts]] in 1966.<ref name=a/> His first book is ''Kanama'' which was published in 1967. It was a teen novel. He worked in [[Swadhin Bangla Betar Kendra]] in 1971.<ref name=a/>\n\nOsman worked as a professor in [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka|Institute of Fine Arts]] from 1995 to 2007. He is a self-educated artist.<ref name=a>{{cite news|url=https://arts.bdnews24.com/?p=12915|title=\u09ac\u09c1\u09b2\u09ac\u09a8 \u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be\u09ce\u0995\u09be\u09b0: \u0995\u09b2\u0995\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u098f\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf \u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09b0\u09be \u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09b2\u09be \u0995\u09b0\u09c7\u099b\u09bf\u09b2 \u09ac\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0995\u09c7|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=14 February 2020|website=bdnews24.com|language=bn}}</ref> He involved in translating books too.\n\n==Awards and recongnition==\nOsman was awarded [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] in 1973 for his contribution in juvenile literature.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u098f\u0995\u09be\u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09bf \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |url=https://banglaacademy.portal.gov.bd/site/page/4b4922ae-d2be-4478-b9bf-08b5dbf50cf2 |website=Bangla Academy|language=bn|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osman, Bulbon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male novelists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi academics]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi translators]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi painters]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Hooghly district]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Bangla Academy Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox person\n| name = Bulbon Osman\n| image = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1940|03|18}}\n| birth_place = Jhamatia, [[Howrah district|Howrah]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]]\n| awards = [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1973)\n| relatives = [[Shawkat Osman]] (father)<br>[[Yeafesh Osman]] (brother)\n| alma_mater = [[University of Dhaka]]\n}}\n'''Bulbon Osman''' (born 18 March 1940) is a [[Bangladesh]]i academic, writer and artist. He was conferred [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] in 1973 for his contribution in juvenile literature.\n\n==Early life and education==\nOsman was born on 18 March 1940 at his maternal house at Jhamatia in [[Howrah district|Howrah]].<ref name=a/> He is the eldest son of [[Shawkat Osman]] and Saleha Osman. His brother [[Yeafesh Osman]] is the incumbent minister of [[Ministry of Science and Technology (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://web.dailyjanakantha.com/details/article/421901/\u0995\u09a5\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c0-\u09b6\u0993\u0995\u09a4-\u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0-\u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u0995\u09c0-\u0986\u099c/|title=\u0995\u09a5\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa\u09c0 \u09b6\u0993\u0995\u09a4 \u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u0995\u09c0 \u0986\u099c|date=13 March 2019|accessdate=14 February 2020|newspaper=Janakantha|language=bn}}</ref>\n\nOsman's paternal house is situated at Sabalsinghapur in [[Hooghly district|Hooghly]].<ref name=a/> His family moved to [[Chittagong]] in 1950. After completing school and college life from there he got admitted into [[University of Dhaka]]. He was a student of the sociology department of the institution.<ref name=a/>\n\n==Career==\nOsman was appointed as a lecturer of the art related sociology at [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka|East Pakistan College of Arts and Crafts]] in 1966.<ref name=a/> His first book is ''Kanama'' which was published in 1967. It was a teen novel. He worked in [[Swadhin Bangla Betar Kendra]] in 1971.<ref name=a/>\n\nOsman worked as a professor in [[Faculty of Fine Arts, University of Dhaka|Institute of Fine Arts]] from 1995 to 2007. He is a self-educated artist.<ref name=a>{{cite news|url=https://arts.bdnews24.com/?p=12915|title=\u09ac\u09c1\u09b2\u09ac\u09a8 \u0993\u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b8\u09be\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09be\u09ce\u0995\u09be\u09b0: \u0995\u09b2\u0995\u09be\u09a4\u09be\u09af\u09bc \u098f\u0995\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf \u09ae\u09c1\u09b8\u09b2\u09bf\u09ae\u09b0\u09be \u09b9\u09be\u09ae\u09b2\u09be \u0995\u09b0\u09c7\u099b\u09bf\u09b2 \u09ac\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0995\u09c7|date=9 June 2017|accessdate=14 February 2020|website=bdnews24.com|language=bn}}</ref> He involved in translating books too.\n\n==Awards and recongnition==\nOsman was awarded [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] in 1973 for his contribution in juvenile literature.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u098f\u0995\u09be\u09a1\u09c7\u09ae\u09bf \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 |url=https://banglaacademy.portal.gov.bd/site/page/4b4922ae-d2be-4478-b9bf-08b5dbf50cf2 |website=Bangla Academy|language=bn|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Osman, Bulbon}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male novelists]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi academics]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi translators]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi painters]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Hooghly district]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Bangla Academy Award]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulbon_Osman"}
{"title_page": "Budhindranath Delihial Bhattacharya", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=December 2017}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=December 2017}}\n{{one source|date=December 2017}}\n{{tone|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n[[File:Budhindranath_Delihial_Bhatta.jpg|thumb|Author's description page photograph taken from the Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary, First Edition, published in 1931.]]\n[[File:Budhindranath_Delihial_Bhatta_(Smoronik_Cover_Photo).jpg|thumb|Portrait shot of Budhindranath Delihial Bhattacharya, published sometime between 1930 and 1940.]]\n\n'''[[Budhindra]] Nath Delihial Bhattacharya''' (1865 - 1945) also known as '''Budhi Babu''', '''Budhindra Nath Bhattacharya''', is renowned for his work ''The Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionaries'', which was first published in 1931. He was also a tea planter of The Crown of England, which later came under the [[Legislative Council of Eastern Bengal and Assam|Governments of Assam & West Bengal.]]\n\n==Early life and education==\nHis father's name was Dharmadutta Bhattacharya and his mother's name was Aai Keteki Devi, of Nowgong, Assam. Budhindranath left a volume of literary works as a dramatist, author, editor, and lexicographer.\n\nBudhindranath went to the Government High School, Nagaon, under the patronage of Rai Bahadur Gunabhiram Baruah. He was a talented student. In 1885, he passed the entrance examination and got admitted to the General Assembly Institution, now called \"City College, Kolkata City College\", where he earned a degree in Fine Arts. In Jaipur, he met Rai Bahadur Radhakanta Handique, Satyanath Bora and other prominent personalities of pre-independent India who later became his close companions. Despite his talent, he had to leave his college education due to his family's financial situation.\n\n==Early professional life & King Edward VIIth's coronation==\nOn 28 July 1888, after arriving at Jorhaat, Budhindranath started living in a small cottage  at the J. B. Road (Babu Ali). He began working  as a school teacher at the [[Jorhat Govt. Boys' H.S and M.P. School|Jorhaat Government High School]] while staying at the cottage. Later, he visited Dhaka, Shillong and a few other places, after which, in 1893, he joined the Jorhat Court as the Criminal Peskar. A few years later, he was promoted to the position of Head Clerk on 17 November 1911, at the Office of the Deputy Commissioner, Jorhat. During that period, in 1894, he was given a piece of land by then Sattradhikar (Head Monk) of the Garmur Sattra, near Malow Ali. He built a humble abode at the location and completed the construction process by 1897. In 1890, Budhi Babu married Rukmini (Golapi), daughter of Gadadhar Sarmah Borthakur of the Matigarung family. The couple had five sons and three daughters, who were saved by Kapindranath Bhattacharya, the sole survivor of Budhindranath's family.\n\nBudhindranath visited [[England]] in 1902, as [[Jagannath Barooah College|Raibahadur Jaggannath Baruah's]] secretary on [[Edward VII|King Edward VIIth's]] Coronation. His travelogue, ''Bilaat Jaatra'', provides exciting glimpses of Britain and pre-independent India, especially Assam, at the beginning of the last century, before the start of World War I.\n\n==Later professional life and the publication of the Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary==\nAfter his retirement in 1920, Budhindranath set up a small tea garden at Golaghat Dighalihula, and started as an independent business person. A year later, in 1924, he was appointed valuer at the [[Golaghat Municipal Board|Golaghat Municipality Office]]. During this period, he was assigned as a Government translator to the East Bengal & Assam Governments.  His contributions to the cause of the [[Culture of Assam|Assamese culture]] and literature during this period were given recognition. In addition to being one of the founding members of the iconic [[Jorhat]] Theatre, he cared deeply about his country and the Assamese literature in pre-independent India. He was also a member of  the Society for the Progress of the Assamese Language. Under this, he contributed actively for the betterment of the Assamese culture and society. Bhattacharya died at the age of 80.\n\n==Notable works==\nDramas:\n\n* ''Romoni Gabhoru'' (1895)\n* ''Pandav Parichay''\n* ''Chitrangada Milan''\n* ''Chengeli Gaonburah''\n\nBooks:\n\n* The Scientific Essence of Hindu Religion\n* Bilaat Probaxhi Asomiya\n\nNewspapers & Magazines to which he contributed his writing:\n\n* Times of Assam\n* Advocate of Assam\n* Assam Bilashini\n* Indian Mirror\n* National Guardian\n* Amritbazar\n* Jayanti\n* Journal of the Assam Sahitya Sabha\n\nNewspapers (With Sahityarathna Chandradhar Baruah):\n\n* ''Darpan''\n\nDictionary:\n\n* The Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary (First Edition, 14 October 1931)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\nThe Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary=By Budhindranath Bhattacharya|Smoronik - A tribute to Lexicographer Budhindranath Delihial Bhattacharya=Compiled by Jorhat Theatre, Edited by Santantu Thakur & Printed & Published by Abhijit Bhattacharya at New Era Media Services, Jorhat. 2003.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:City College, Kolkata alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Indian lexicographers]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=December 2017}}\n{{notability|Biographies|date=December 2017}}\n{{one source|date=December 2017}}\n{{tone|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n[[File:Budhindranath_Delihial_Bhatta.jpg|thumb|Author's description page photograph taken from the Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary, First Edition, published in 1931.]]\n[[File:Budhindranath_Delihial_Bhatta_(Smoronik_Cover_Photo).jpg|thumb|Portrait shot of Budhindranath Delihial Bhattacharya, published sometime between 1930 and 1940.]]\n\n'''[[Budhindra]] Nath Delihial Bhattacharya''' (1865 - 1945) also known as '''Budhi Babu''', '''Budhindra Nath Bhattacharya''', is renowned for his work ''The Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionaries'', which was first published in 1931. He was also a tea planter of The Crown of England, which later came under the [[Legislative Council of Eastern Bengal and Assam|Governments of Assam & West Bengal.]]\n\n==Early life and education==\nHis father's name was Dharmadutta Bhattacharya and his mother's name was Aai Keteki Devi, of Nowgong, Assam. Budhindranath left a volume of literary works as a dramatist, author, editor, and lexicographer. \n\nBudhindranath went to the Government High School, Nagaon, under the patronage of Rai Bahadur Gunabhiram Baruah. He was a talented student. In 1885, he passed the entrance examination and got admitted to the General Assembly Institution, now called \"City College, Kolkata City College\", where he earned a degree in Fine Arts. In Jaipur, he met Rai Bahadur Radhakanta Handique, Satyanath Bora and other prominent personalities of pre-independent India who later became his close companions. Despite his talent, he had to leave his college education due to his family's financial situation.\n\n==Early professional life & King Edward VIIth's coronation==\nOn 28 July 1888, after arriving at Jorhaat, Budhindranath started living in a small cottage  at the J. B. Road (Babu Ali). He began working  as a school teacher at the [[Jorhat Govt. Boys' H.S and M.P. School|Jorhaat Government High School]] while staying at the cottage. Later, he visited Dhaka, Shillong and a few other places, after which, in 1893, he joined the Jorhat Court as the Criminal Peskar. A few years later, he was promoted to the position of Head Clerk on 17 November 1911, at the Office of the Deputy Commissioner, Jorhat. During that period, in 1894, he was given a piece of land by then Sattradhikar (Head Monk) of the Garmur Sattra, near Malow Ali. He built a humble abode at the location and completed the construction process by 1897. In 1890, Budhi Babu married Rukmini (Golapi), daughter of Gadadhar Sarmah Borthakur of the Matigarung family. The couple had five sons and three daughters, who were saved by Kapindranath Bhattacharya, the sole survivor of Budhindranath's family.\n\nBudhindranath visited [[England]] in 1902, as [[Jagannath Barooah College|Raibahadur Jaggannath Baruah's]] secretary on [[Edward VII|King Edward VIIth's]] Coronation. His travelogue, ''Bilaat Jaatra'', provides exciting glimpses of Britain and pre-independent India, especially Assam, at the beginning of the last century, before the start of World War I.\n\n==Later professional life and the publication of the Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary==\nAfter his retirement in 1920, Budhindranath set up a small tea garden at Golaghat Dighalihula, and started as an independent business person. A year later, in 1924, he was appointed valuer at the [[Golaghat Municipal Board|Golaghat Municipality Office]]. During this period, he was assigned as a Government translator to the East Bengal & Assam Governments.  His contributions to the cause of the [[Culture of Assam|Assamese culture]] and literature during this period were given recognition. In addition to being one of the founding members of the iconic [[Jorhat]] Theatre, he cared deeply about his country and the Assamese literature in pre-independent India. He was also a member of  the Society for the Progress of the Assamese Language. Under this, he contributed actively for the betterment of the Assamese culture and society. Bhattacharya died at the age of 80.\n\n==Notable works==\nDramas:\n\n* ''Romoni Gabhoru'' (1895)\n* ''Pandav Parichay''\n* ''Chitrangada Milan''\n* ''Chengeli Gaonburah''\n\nBooks:\n\n* The Scientific Essence of Hindu Religion\n* Bilaat Probaxhi Asomiya\n\nNewspapers & Magazines to which he contributed his writing:\n\n* Times of Assam\n* Advocate of Assam\n* Assam Bilashini\n* Indian Mirror\n* National Guardian\n* Amritbazar\n* Jayanti\n* Journal of the Assam Sahitya Sabha\n\nNewspapers (With Sahityarathna Chandradhar Baruah):\n\n* ''Darpan''\n\nDictionary:\n\n* The Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary (First Edition, 14 October 1931)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\nThe Pronouncing Anglo Assamese Dictionary=By Budhindranath Bhattacharya|Smoronik - A tribute to Lexicographer Budhindranath Delihial Bhattacharya=Compiled by Jorhat Theatre, Edited by Santantu Thakur & Printed & Published by Abhijit Bhattacharya at New Era Media Services, Jorhat. 2003.\n\n[[Category:1865 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:City College, Kolkata alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Indian lexicographers]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Budhindranath_Delihial_Bhattacharya"}
